\title{R6 Class for unified input file tracking and staleness detection}
\description{
The \code{InputsManifest} class provides a unified system for tracking all input
data files used by the IMPACTncd simulation. It detects file changes and
determines which downstream artifacts (synthpops, compiled RR \code{.fst} files,
PARF files) need regeneration based on the model's causal structure.
}
\details{
This class replaces the previous fragmented tracking mechanisms
(\code{fileversion.csv}, synthpop meta YAML, \code{zenodo_manifest.csv}) with a
single manifest CSV that records relative paths and \code{xxhash64} checksums
for all data files in the \verb{inputs/} directory.
\subsection{Manifest CSV format}{

The manifest is stored at \code{simulation/inputs_manifest.csv} with columns:\tabular{lll}{
   Column \tab Type \tab Description \cr
   \code{relative_path} \tab character \tab Path relative to \verb{inputs/} (portable) \cr
   \code{hash} \tab character \tab xxhash64 checksum of file contents \cr
   \code{size_bytes} \tab numeric \tab File size in bytes \cr
   \code{mtime} \tab character \tab ISO 8601 modification time \cr
   \code{category} \tab character \tab Top-level subdirectory name \cr
   \code{zenodo_managed} \tab logical \tab Whether the file is uploaded to Zenodo \cr
}

}

\subsection{Hashing strategy}{

All hashes use \code{xxhash64} via \code{\link[digest:digest]{digest::digest()}}. This is ~10x faster than
MD5, which is critical when scanning 10,000+ parquet files in
\verb{exposure_distributions/}. The \code{compare()} method applies an \strong{mtime
pre-filter}: files whose modification time has not changed since the last
manifest generation are assumed unchanged and not re-hashed, making
incremental checks very fast.
}

\subsection{Causal invalidation}{

The \code{detect_changes()} method maps file changes to downstream artifacts
using the model's causal structure:

\itemize{
\item Changes in \verb{pop_estimates_lsoa/}, \verb{exposure_distributions/},
\verb{mortality/}, or \verb{pop_projections/} invalidate \strong{synthpops}
\item Changes in \verb{RR/*.csvy} files invalidate the corresponding
\strong{compiled RR \code{.fst}} files and downstream \strong{PARF} files
\item Changes in \verb{disease_burden/} data files (not \code{.yaml}) invalidate
that disease's \strong{PARF} files
\item A BFS traversal through the causal graph (built from
\code{design$RR} names) finds \strong{transitively affected} diseases
}
}

\subsection{Output artifact checksums}{

Synthpop and PARF files are too large to re-hash at every simulation
start. Instead, their checksums are embedded in their filenames (e.g.
\verb{synthpop_<hash>_<mc>.fst}, \verb{PARF_<disease>_<hash>.qs}). When upstream
inputs change, the checksum changes, the filename changes, and the old
file is simply not found — triggering automatic regeneration. The
\code{verify_artifact()} method provides an opt-in diagnostic that actually
hashes the file on disk and compares against the filename-embedded hash.
}

\subsection{Zenodo integration}{

Not all files in \verb{inputs/} are uploaded to Zenodo — some are tracked by
git instead. The \code{zenodo_managed} column distinguishes between the two.
Use \code{set_zenodo_dirs()} to mark which directories are Zenodo-managed and
\code{get_zenodo_format()} to extract the Zenodo-managed subset for comparison
with the upload snapshot.
}

\subsection{Parallel hashing}{

When \code{parallel = TRUE} is passed to \code{generate()}, the class uses
\code{\link[parallelly:makeClusterPSOCK]{parallelly::makeClusterPSOCK()}} + \code{\link[parallel:parLapplyLB]{parallel::parLapplyLB()}} with the
standalone \code{.manifest_hash_worker()} function. This follows the project
convention of never forking (which causes segfaults with \code{zip::zip()}
and cannot serialize R6 HTTP connections).
}
}
\section{Typical workflow}{

The manifest is managed automatically by \link[=Simulation]{Simulation$new()}:
\enumerate{
\item On first run, \code{generate()} scans \verb{inputs/} and creates the manifest
\item On subsequent runs, \code{detect_changes()} compares the filesystem
against the stored manifest
\item If changes are found, stale artifacts are deleted and the manifest
is regenerated
\item Existing generation logic (in SynthPop, ExposureEffect, Disease)
automatically recreates deleted artifacts
}
}

\examples{
\dontrun{
# Create and generate a manifest
manifest <- InputsManifest$new(
  inputs_dir = "./inputs",
  manifest_path = "./simulation/inputs_manifest.csv"
)
manifest$generate(parallel = TRUE, n_workers = 4L)
print(manifest)

# Check for changes since last generation
diff <- manifest$compare()
cat("Added:", length(diff$added), "\n")
cat("Modified:", length(diff$modified), "\n")

# Detect which artifacts are affected (requires Design object)
changes <- manifest$detect_changes(design = my_design)
if (changes$affected_synthpops) {
  message("Synthpops need regeneration")
}

# Get aggregate hash for synthpop-relevant inputs
hash <- manifest$get_synthpop_input_hash()

# Mark Zenodo-managed directories
manifest$set_zenodo_dirs(c("RR", "exposure_distributions"))
zenodo_subset <- manifest$get_zenodo_format()

# Verify integrity of a large artifact file (opt-in diagnostic)
result <- manifest$verify_artifact("simulation/parf/PARF_chd_8300ca5a.qs")
cat("Valid:", result$valid, "\n")
}

}
